    {
      "title": "Acceleration and velocity of centre of mass",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Motion of Centre of Mass&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>${{\\vec{r}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\frac{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{{\\vec{r}}}_{\\text{i}}}}{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}}$</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\vec{r}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\frac{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{ }\\!\\!\\Delta\\!\\!\\text{ }{{{\\vec{r}}}_{\\text{i}}}}{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}}$</p><p>${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\frac{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{{\\vec{r}}}_{\\text{i}}}}{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }\\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\vec{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\frac{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{{\\vec{a}}}_{\\text{i}}}}{\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"208\" height=\"164\"></p><p>$\\text{M}{{\\vec{V}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{\\vec{V}}_{\\text{i}}}$</p><p>${{\\text{P}}_{\\text{CM}}}={{\\vec{P}}_{1}}+{{\\vec{P}}_{2}}+{{\\vec{P}}_{3}}+\\ldots \\ldots$.</p><p>Total momentum of system in frame of reference $\\text{S}$ = momentum of CM in same frame of reference $\\text{S}$$=$ vector sum of individual momenta of particles in same frame $\\text{S}$.</p><p>$\\frac{\\text{d}{{{\\vec{P}}}_{\\text{CM}}}}{\\text{dt}}=\\sum {{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{\\vec{a}}_{\\text{i}}}=\\sum \\left( \\frac{\\text{d}{{{\\vec{P}}}_{\\text{i}}}}{\\text{dt}} \\right)=\\sum \\vec{F}_{\\text{i}}^{\\text{ }\\!\\!'\\!\\!\\text{ }}={{\\left( {{{\\vec{F}}}_{\\text{ex}}} \\right)}_{\\text{net }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$</p><p>$\\therefore {{\\vec{F}}_{\\text{ex}}}=\\text{M}{{\\vec{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}$</p><p>${{\\vec{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}=\\left( \\frac{{{{\\vec{F}}}_{\\text{ex}}}}{\\text{M}} \\right)$</p><p>All external forces acting on system of particles can be treated to act on centre of mass of system of particles.</p><p>${{\\text{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}\\left( \\text{x} \\right)=\\frac{{{\\left( {{\\text{F}}_{\\text{ex}}} \\right)}_{\\text{x}}}}{\\text{M}};{{\\text{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}\\left( \\text{y} \\right)=\\frac{{{\\text{F}}_{\\text{ex}}}\\left( \\text{y} \\right)}{\\text{M}};{{\\text{a}}_{\\text{CM}}}\\left( \\text{z} \\right)=\\frac{{{\\text{F}}_{\\text{ex}}}\\left( \\text{z} \\right)}{\\text{M}}$</p><p>$\\vec{P}={{\\vec{P}}_{1}}+{{\\vec{P}}_{2}}$</p><p>$\\left( \\frac{d\\vec{P}}{dt} \\right)=\\left( \\frac{d{{{\\vec{P}}}_{1}}}{dt} \\right)+\\left( \\frac{d{{{\\vec{P}}}_{2}}}{dt} \\right)$</p><p>$=\\left( {{{\\vec{F}}}_{1}}+{{{\\vec{F}}}_{12}} \\right)+\\left( {{{\\vec{F}}}_{2}}+\\left( -{{{\\vec{F}}}_{21}} \\right) \\right)$</p><p>$=\\left( {{{\\vec{F}}}_{1}}+{{{\\vec{F}}}_{2}} \\right)={{\\left( {{{\\vec{F}}}_{\\text{ex}}} \\right)}_{\\text{net }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"257\" height=\"212\"></p><p>In non-inertial frames, the effect of pseudo force must be considered.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db26c03b9dcaf1afe059"
    },
    {
      "title": "Conservation of linear momentum",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Conservation of Linear Momentum&nbsp;</strong></h3><p>The conservation law for linear momentum follows is very close to being just a restatement of Newtons first law that the velocity vector is constant for a body on which no forces act. So you have in a sense already been using this conservation law in various problems involving Newtons laws.</p><p>One of the beauties of Newtons laws is that there are no restriction on what type of macroscopic objects we can apply them. We now embark on the use of Newtons laws to examine systems of particles which in general can have internal motion as well. In this context we shall learn about the conservation laws for Linear and Angular momentum and about the center of mass for an object.</p><p>First it turns out to be handy to introduce the quantity called linear momentum. For a single particle the linear momentum is a vector quantity defined as</p><p>$\\vec{P}=\\text{m}\\vec{v}$</p><p>Using this quantity we can re-write Newtons second law as</p><p>$\\vec{F}=m\\vec{a}=m\\frac{d\\vec{v}}{\\text{dt}}=\\frac{d\\vec{P}}{\\text{dt}}$</p><p>Interestingly this was actually the form which Sir Isaac Newton himself chose to work with. A special case that we have often considered before is when</p><p>$\\vec{F}=\\vec{0} \\Rightarrow \\vec{P} \\text{ is } \\text{ a } \\text{ constant } \\text{ }$</p><p>If our object under considerations consists of many individual \"sub\" objects then we can still define a momentum for that system of particles</p><p>$\\vec{P}=\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,{{\\vec{P}}_{\\text{i}}}=\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{i}}}$</p><p>To distinguish it from the linear momentum of individual particles we use a large $\\text{P}$ for the momentum of a many particle system. Taking the time derivative of this equation we get</p><p>$\\frac{d\\vec{P}}{dt}=\\underset{i}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,\\frac{d\\vec{P}}{dt}=\\underset{i}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,{{\\vec{F}}_{i}}={{\\vec{F}}_{net}}$</p><p>So,</p><p><strong>The linear momentum of a system of particles is conserved when no net external force acts on that system. </strong>It is important to note that no net force does not mean that no forces act. Internal forces are allowed to occur because Newtons third law guarantees that these forces come in action-reaction pairs and hence they cancel out exactly when we add them up to get the net force, ${{\\vec{F}}_{\\text{net }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$. Thus the presence of large internal forces does not invalidate the conservation of linear momentum.</p><p><strong>Note : </strong>Suppose a system consists of more than one particle (or bodies). Net external force on the system in a particular direction is zero. Initially the centre of mass of the system is at rest, then obviously the centre of mass will not move along that particular direction even though some particles (or bodies) of the system may move along that direction. The following example will illustrate the above theory.</p>",
      "position": 1,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db26c03b9dcaf1afe05a"
    },
    {
      "title": "Kinetic energy assosiated with centre of mass",
      "conceptBody": "<h3>Kinetic energy assosiated with centre of mass</h3><p>The kinetic energy of a system of particles can be written as the sum of two terms :</p><p>(i) The kinetic energy associated with the motion of centre of mass, $\\frac{1}{2}\\text{Mv}_{\\text{COM}}^{2}$ where $\\text{M}$ is the total mass of the system and</p><p>(ii) The kinetic energy associated with the motion of the particles of the system relative to the centre of mass, $\\sum \\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{u}_{\\text{i}}^{2}$, where ${{\\vec{u}}_{\\text{i}}}$ is the velocity of the ${{\\text{i}}^{\\text{th }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ particle relative to the centre of mass.</p><p>The kinetic energy of a system of the individual particles.</p><p>K.E. $={{\\sum }_{\\text{i}}}{{\\text{K}}_{\\text{i}}}={{\\sum }_{\\text{i}}}\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{v}_{\\text{i}}^{2}$</p><p>The velocity of each particle can be written as the sum of the velocity of the centre of mass ${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{COM}}}$ and the velocity of the particle relative to centre of mass ${{\\vec{u}}_{\\text{i}}}$.</p><p>${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{i}}}={{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{COM}}}+{{\\vec{u}}_{\\text{i}}}$</p><p>Then K.E. $={{\\sum }_{\\text{i}}}\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\left( {{{\\vec{v}}}_{\\text{i}}}\\cdot {{{\\vec{v}}}_{\\text{i}}} \\right)={{\\sum }_{\\text{i}}}\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\left( {{{\\vec{v}}}_{\\text{COM}}}+{{{\\vec{u}}}_{\\text{i}}} \\right)\\cdot \\left( {{{\\vec{v}}}_{\\text{COM}}}+{{{\\vec{u}}}_{\\text{i}}} \\right)$</p><p>$=\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{v}_{\\text{COM}}^{2}+\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{u}_{1}^{2}+{{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{COM}}}\\cdot \\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{\\vec{u}}_{\\text{i}}}$</p><p>In the last term we have removed ${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{COM}}}$ from the sum because it is same for each particle. The quantity ${{\\sum }_{\\text{i}}}{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}{{\\vec{u}}_{\\text{i}}}$ is the total momentum of the system relative to the centre of mass. This quantity is necessarily zero. Thus,</p><p>$\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ K}\\text{.E}\\text{. }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }=\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{v}_{\\text{COM}}^{2}+\\underset{\\text{i}}{\\mathop \\sum }\\,\\frac{1}{2}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{\\text{i}}}\\text{u}_{1}^{2}+\\frac{1}{2}\\text{Mv}_{\\text{COM}}^{2}+{{\\text{K}}_{\\text{rel}}}$</p><p>where $M$ is the total mass and ${{K}_{\\text{rel }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}}$ is the kinetic energy of the particles relative to the centre of mass. When there are no external force, ${{\\vec{v}}_{\\text{COM}}}$ is constant and the kinetic energy associated with bulk motion $\\left( \\frac{1}{2}\\text{Mv}_{\\text{COM}}^{2} \\right)$ does not change. Only the relative kinetic energy $\\left( {{\\text{K}}_{\\text{rel }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }}} \\right)$ can change in isolated system.</p>",
      "position": 2,
      "qcConcept": "66a0db26c03b9dcaf1afe05b"
    }
